{"title_page": "Pavol Skalick\u00fd", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Pavol Skalicky\n| image = {{CSS image crop|Image         = 20150207 1816 Ice Hockey AUT SVK 9750.jpg|bSize         = 500|cWidth        = 230|cHeight       = 300|oTop          = 40|oLeft         = 225|Location = center}}\n| caption =\n| image_size = 230px\n| team = [[BK Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav]]\n| league = [[Czech Extraliga|ELH]]\n| former_teams = [[HC Ko\u0161ice]]<br>[[\u00d6rebro HK]]<br>[[HC Slovan Bratislava]]<br>[[HC '05 Bansk\u00e1 Bystrica]]\n| ntl_team = Slovakia\n| position = [[Forward (ice hockey)|Forward]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes |1995|10|09}} \n| birth_place = [[Gelnica]], Slovakia\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 5\n| weight_lb = 207\n| shoots = Right\n| draft = \n| career_start = 2013\n| career_end =\n}}\n'''Pavol Skalicky''' (born October 9, 1995) is a [[Slovakia|Slovak]] professional [[ice hockey]] player. He is currently playing for [[Lukko|Rauman Lukko]] in the Finnish [[Liiga]].\n\nSkalicky made his [[Swedish Hockey League]] debut playing with [[\u00d6rebro HK]] during the [[2014\u201315 SHL season]].<ref>{{citeweb| url = http://manager.aftonbladet.se/se/shl-manager-spring-2015/players/pavol_skalicky | title = SHL manager spring 2015 | website = aftonbladet.se | date = 2015-04-02 | accessdate = 2015-04-02}}</ref> After three seasons in the [[Kontinental Hockey League]] with Slovak club, [[HC Slovan Bratislava]], Skalicky left as a free agent in securing a one-year contract with Czech top tier club, BK Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav, of the ELH on May 1, 2018.<ref>{{citeweb| url = https://bkboleslav.cz/clanek.asp?id=Prichazi-Vondrka-Novacky-jsou-take-Stastny-Planek-a-Skalicky-6097 | publisher = [[BK Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav]] | date = 2018-05-01 | accessdate = 2018-05-01 | language = Czech | title = Boleslav announce three new signings }}</ref>\n \n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{icehockeystats}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skalicky, Pavol}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:HC '05 Bansk\u00e1 Bystrica players]]\n[[Category:HC Ko\u0161ice players]]\n[[Category:\u00d6rebro HK players]]\n[[Category:Slovak ice hockey forwards]]\n[[Category:HC Slovan Bratislava players]]\n[[Category:People from Gelnica]]\n\n\n{{Slovakia-icehockey-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Pavol Skalicky\n| image = {{CSS image crop|Image         = 20150207 1816 Ice Hockey AUT SVK 9750.jpg|bSize         = 500|cWidth        = 230|cHeight       = 300|oTop          = 40|oLeft         = 225|Location = center}}\n| caption =\n| image_size = 230px\n| team = [[BK Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav]]\n| league = [[Czech Extraliga|ELH]]\n| former_teams = [[HC Ko\u0161ice]]<br>[[\u00d6rebro HK]]<br>[[HC Slovan Bratislava]]<br>[[HC '05 Bansk\u00e1 Bystrica]]\n| ntl_team = Slovakia\n| position = [[Forward (ice hockey)|Forward]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes |1995|10|09}} \n| birth_place = [[Gelnica]], Slovakia\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 5\n| weight_lb = 207\n| shoots = Right\n| draft = \n| career_start = 2013\n| career_end =\n}}\n'''Pavol Skalicky''' (born October 9, 1995) is a [[Slovakia|Slovak]] professional [[ice hockey]] player. He is currently playing with [[BK Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav]] of the [[Czech Extraliga]] (ELH).\n\nSkalicky made his [[Swedish Hockey League]] debut playing with [[\u00d6rebro HK]] during the [[2014\u201315 SHL season]].<ref>{{citeweb| url = http://manager.aftonbladet.se/se/shl-manager-spring-2015/players/pavol_skalicky | title = SHL manager spring 2015 | website = aftonbladet.se | date = 2015-04-02 | accessdate = 2015-04-02}}</ref> After three seasons in the [[Kontinental Hockey League]] with Slovak club, [[HC Slovan Bratislava]], Skalicky left as a free agent in securing a one-year contract with Czech top tier club, BK Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav, of the ELH on May 1, 2018.<ref>{{citeweb| url = https://bkboleslav.cz/clanek.asp?id=Prichazi-Vondrka-Novacky-jsou-take-Stastny-Planek-a-Skalicky-6097 | publisher = [[BK Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav]] | date = 2018-05-01 | accessdate = 2018-05-01 | language = Czech | title = Boleslav announce three new signings }}</ref>\n \n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{icehockeystats}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skalicky, Pavol}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:HC '05 Bansk\u00e1 Bystrica players]]\n[[Category:HC Ko\u0161ice players]]\n[[Category:\u00d6rebro HK players]]\n[[Category:Slovak ice hockey forwards]]\n[[Category:HC Slovan Bratislava players]]\n[[Category:People from Gelnica]]\n\n\n{{Slovakia-icehockey-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nexustron", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed the team Skalicky plays for since he joined a new team today (April 15).", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pavol_Skalick%C3%BD"}
{"title_page": "George H. W. Bush vomiting incident", "text_new": "\n\n\n==Effects of the incident==\nThe incident was widely reported,<ref name=\"collapse\">{{cite news|first=Michael|last=Wines|title=Bush Collapses at State Dinner With the Japanese|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/01/09/world/bush-in-japan-bush-collapses-at-state-dinner-with-the-japanese.html|quote=President Bush fell suddenly ill and collapsed at a state dinner being given for him Wednesday night at the home of the Japanese Prime Minister.|work=[[New York Times]]|date=January 9, 1992|accessdate=2009-08-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090928031127/http://www.nytimes.com/1992/01/09/world/bush-in-japan-bush-collapses-at-state-dinner-with-the-japanese.html|archive-date=2009-09-28|url-status=live}}</ref> coming just weeks before the New Hampshire Primary, and quickly became fodder for the nation's comedians. Footage of the President vomiting was broadcast on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] network. The incident was parodied by ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''<ref>https://www.newsweek.com/25-years-ago-today-george-h-w-bush-vomited-prime-minister-japan-538581</ref> with a mock documentary, with [[Barbara Bush]] trying to escape by crawling across the table, echoing the [[assassination of John F. Kennedy]] when [[Jacqueline Kennedy]] crawled across the rear of the limousine. \n\nShortly after the incident, an [[Idaho]] man, James Edward Smith, called [[CNN]] posing as the president's physician and claimed that Bush had died. A CNN employee entered the information into a centralized computer used by both CNN and sister network [[HLN (TV channel)|CNN Headline News]], and Headline News nearly aired it before it could be verified. Smith was subsequently questioned by the Secret Service and hospitalized at a private mental health facility for evaluation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1992-01-10/entertainment/ca-1610_1_cnn-s-headline-news|title=CNN Averts Hoax About Bush's 'Death'|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|last=McDougal|first=Dennis|date=1992-01-10|access-date=2013-04-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130131021137/http://articles.latimes.com/1992-01-10/entertainment/ca-1610_1_cnn-s-headline-news|archive-date=2013-01-31|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn Japan, even several years later, Bush was remembered for this event.<ref name=\"Time Asia\">Peter McKillop, \"Letter from Japan: Back to the Future: Will George W. Bush carry on his father's (barfing) legacy?, ''Time Asia'' found at [http://www.time.com/time/asia/asiabuzz/2001/01/20/ Time Asia archives] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090412144009/http://www.time.com/time/asia/asiabuzz/2001/01/20/ |date=2009-04-12 }}. Accessed September 19, 2009.</ref> According to the ''Encyclopedia of political communication'', \"The incident caused a wave of late night television jokes and ridicule in the international community, even coining ''Busshu-suru'' ({{lang|ja|\u30d6\u30c3\u30b7\u30e5\u3059\u308b}}) which literally means 'to do the Bush thing'.\"<ref name=\"Encyclopedia\">Lynda Lee Kaid and Christina Holtz-Bacha, ''Encyclopedia of Political Communication'', Volume 1, p. 72, (SAGE, 2008), {{ISBN|978-1-4129-1799-5}}, found at [https://books.google.com/books?id=-woKG0HTstwC&pg=PA72&dq=Bushu-suru#v=onepage&q=Bushu-suru&f=false Google Books]. Accessed September 19, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn 1993, the incident was spoofed in the comedy film ''[[Hot Shots! Part Deux]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/film-its-not-hot-and-theres-no-shots-in-it-hot-shots-part-deux-is-the-latest-exercise-in-movie-1461431.html|title=FILM / It's not hot and there's no shots in it: Hot Shots: Part Deux] is the latest exercise in movie parody from Jim Abrahams. Kevin Jackson met him|author=Kevin Jackson|date=August 16, 1993|work=The Independent|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180902162948/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/film-its-not-hot-and-theres-no-shots-in-it-hot-shots-part-deux-is-the-latest-exercise-in-movie-1461431.html|archive-date=September 2, 2018|access-date=September 2, 2018}}</ref> According to a 2007 [[listicle]] published by ''[[USA Today]]'', the incident was one of the top \"25 memorable public meltdowns that had us talking and laughing or cringing over the past quarter-century.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/top25-meltdowns.htm|work=USA Today|title=They did what, said what?|date=May 7, 2007|access-date=2017-08-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120416154111/http://www.usatoday.com/news/top25-meltdowns.htm|archive-date=2012-04-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Jimmy Carter rabbit incident]]\n* [[Bill Clinton haircut controversy]]\n* [[Dick Cheney hunting incident]]\n* [[2009 U.S. state dinner security breaches]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{George H. W. Bush}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:George H. W. Bush Vomiting Incident}}\n[[Category:1992 in American politics]]\n[[Category:1992 in international relations]]\n[[Category:1992 in Japan]]\n[[Category:January 1992 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Japan\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Presidency of George H. W. Bush|Vomiting incident]]\n[[Category:Vomiting|Bush, George H. W. vomiting incident]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Bush-japanese-pm.jpeg|thumb|right|Frame from an ABC News video of First Lady [[Barbara Bush]] holding a napkin in front of President [[George H. W. Bush]]'s face as he vomits.]] On January 8, 1992, about 8:20&nbsp;p.m [[Japan Standard Time|JST]], while attending a banquet hosted by the [[Prime Minister of Japan]], [[Kiichi Miyazawa]], [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[George H. W. Bush]] fainted, after [[vomiting]] in Miyazawa's lap. \n\n==History==\nOn January 8, 1992, Bush was attending a state event for 135 diplomats held at the home of the Japanese Prime Minister, near the end of the President's 12-day trade-oriented trip through Asia. Earlier that day Bush had played a [[doubles tennis|doubles]] [[tennis]] match in which the [[Emperor of Japan]] [[Akihito]] and his son the Crown Prince [[Naruhito, Crown Prince of Japan|Naruhito]] beat Bush and his partner, a former U.S. ambassador to Japan.\n\n==Effects of the incident==\nThe incident was widely reported,<ref name=\"collapse\">{{cite news|first=Michael|last=Wines|title=Bush Collapses at State Dinner With the Japanese|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/01/09/world/bush-in-japan-bush-collapses-at-state-dinner-with-the-japanese.html|quote=President Bush fell suddenly ill and collapsed at a state dinner being given for him Wednesday night at the home of the Japanese Prime Minister.|work=[[New York Times]]|date=January 9, 1992|accessdate=2009-08-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090928031127/http://www.nytimes.com/1992/01/09/world/bush-in-japan-bush-collapses-at-state-dinner-with-the-japanese.html|archive-date=2009-09-28|url-status=live}}</ref> coming just weeks before the New Hampshire Primary, and quickly became fodder for the nation's comedians. Footage of the President vomiting was broadcast on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] network. The incident was parodied by ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''<ref>https://www.newsweek.com/25-years-ago-today-george-h-w-bush-vomited-prime-minister-japan-538581</ref> with a mock documentary, with [[Barbara Bush]] trying to escape by crawling across the table, echoing the [[assassination of John F. Kennedy]] when [[Jacqueline Kennedy]] crawled across the rear of the limousine. \n\nShortly after the incident, an [[Idaho]] man, James Edward Smith, called [[CNN]] posing as the president's physician and claimed that Bush had died. A CNN employee entered the information into a centralized computer used by both CNN and sister network [[HLN (TV channel)|CNN Headline News]], and Headline News nearly aired it before it could be verified. Smith was subsequently questioned by the Secret Service and hospitalized at a private mental health facility for evaluation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1992-01-10/entertainment/ca-1610_1_cnn-s-headline-news|title=CNN Averts Hoax About Bush's 'Death'|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|last=McDougal|first=Dennis|date=1992-01-10|access-date=2013-04-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130131021137/http://articles.latimes.com/1992-01-10/entertainment/ca-1610_1_cnn-s-headline-news|archive-date=2013-01-31|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn Japan, even several years later, Bush was remembered for this event.<ref name=\"Time Asia\">Peter McKillop, \"Letter from Japan: Back to the Future: Will George W. Bush carry on his father's (barfing) legacy?, ''Time Asia'' found at [http://www.time.com/time/asia/asiabuzz/2001/01/20/ Time Asia archives] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090412144009/http://www.time.com/time/asia/asiabuzz/2001/01/20/ |date=2009-04-12 }}. Accessed September 19, 2009.</ref> According to the ''Encyclopedia of political communication'', \"The incident caused a wave of late night television jokes and ridicule in the international community, even coining ''Busshu-suru'' ({{lang|ja|\u30d6\u30c3\u30b7\u30e5\u3059\u308b}}) which literally means 'to do the Bush thing'.\"<ref name=\"Encyclopedia\">Lynda Lee Kaid and Christina Holtz-Bacha, ''Encyclopedia of Political Communication'', Volume 1, p. 72, (SAGE, 2008), {{ISBN|978-1-4129-1799-5}}, found at [https://books.google.com/books?id=-woKG0HTstwC&pg=PA72&dq=Bushu-suru#v=onepage&q=Bushu-suru&f=false Google Books]. Accessed September 19, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn 1993, the incident was spoofed in the comedy film ''[[Hot Shots! Part Deux]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/film-its-not-hot-and-theres-no-shots-in-it-hot-shots-part-deux-is-the-latest-exercise-in-movie-1461431.html|title=FILM / It's not hot and there's no shots in it: Hot Shots: Part Deux] is the latest exercise in movie parody from Jim Abrahams. Kevin Jackson met him|author=Kevin Jackson|date=August 16, 1993|work=The Independent|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180902162948/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/film-its-not-hot-and-theres-no-shots-in-it-hot-shots-part-deux-is-the-latest-exercise-in-movie-1461431.html|archive-date=September 2, 2018|access-date=September 2, 2018}}</ref> According to a 2007 [[listicle]] published by ''[[USA Today]]'', the incident was one of the top \"25 memorable public meltdowns that had us talking and laughing or cringing over the past quarter-century.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/top25-meltdowns.htm|work=USA Today|title=They did what, said what?|date=May 7, 2007|access-date=2017-08-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120416154111/http://www.usatoday.com/news/top25-meltdowns.htm|archive-date=2012-04-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Jimmy Carter rabbit incident]]\n* [[Bill Clinton haircut controversy]]\n* [[Dick Cheney hunting incident]]\n* [[2009 U.S. state dinner security breaches]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{George H. W. Bush}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:George H. W. Bush Vomiting Incident}}\n[[Category:1992 in American politics]]\n[[Category:1992 in international relations]]\n[[Category:1992 in Japan]]\n[[Category:January 1992 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Japan\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Presidency of George H. W. Bush|Vomiting incident]]\n[[Category:Vomiting|Bush, George H. W. vomiting incident]]\n", "name_user": "2601:2c1:4380:68d0:3c7f:590a:641:799b", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_H._W._Bush_vomiting_incident"}
